UP|44|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's start with Ally's overcall. I think it is fine, the only downside is partner will lead spades if they are defending. On the other hand you should lay claim to the spade suit when you can. At the one level, I think it is okay to overcall with a bad 5 card suit, although not everyone agrees. |
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For my bid, I had a choice of pass, negative double, or diamond raise. With 5 diamonds and a bad hand, I thought the preemptive raise was the best tactic. I would not quarrel with a negative double, but because they have spades, they can outbid us. Had Ally overcalled hearts and I had spades, then a negative double makes more sense tactically, because then we can outbid them. |
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Soupy should worry about whether to bid 3 or 4. If his King of diamonds was in another suit, hearts for example, then I probably recommend 4. But with it being in diamonds I think 3 is a good bid. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As far as the defense, it is hard for Elizabeth to read that I have a singleton, but she should not think I have 4. I have 5 diamonds, and 2 or 3 spades. Ally did not bid hearts and is unlikely to have more than 4 and probably 3. So, I have 3 or 4 hearts and could be 2-3-5-3 possibly, which would give Ally 2 clubs. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Given my lead, I might have three. I can't have two, because I led the 4 and Elizabeth can see the three and two. Therefore, I either have one or three. So, although Elizabeth does not know for sure what I have, an expert partner who counts out the hands might figure out I have one.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


