NT||UP|52|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Lots to discuss both bidding and play. Even assuming you play light openers, I strongly prefer 2D over 1D by West. It is much more descriptive as well as preemptive. Partner is a passed hand, so there is no chance you have game and might as well make it difficult for the opponents.  |
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I also do not agree with Elizabeth's double. Unless you are planning to double and correct, you need to be at least 4-3 in the majors. Sometimes you can be 3-3 with two good 3 card suits, but 2-3  does not cut it. Neither her suit nor her hand are good enough for a double and correct. Further, 2C is somewhat preemptive. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Ally's redouble was fine. My 3 hearts should show a moderate hand with long hearts. I am counting on partner to have at least three. My diamond void is golden as is my Ace of spades. I almost have a 4 heart bid. And I would not blame someone if they bid 4 which is why double by Elizabeth can work out very badly. She can bid 2C or 1N, although her diamond stopper is iffy, she is hoping I have the Queen at least. Pass is okay too. |
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play I am in great danger of losing control of this hand, by having the opponents make me ruff diamonds. So, I want to set up clubs before drawing any trumps. I was also hoping the situation was the way it was. West should duck the Ace of clubs, as he has no reason to think I have 5 clubs. |
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to whether Ally should ruff, it is reasonable for her to think I have the Ace of clubs. However, she knows she has 2 natural trump tricks  and that argues against ruffing. Usually, you should avoid ruffing with natural trump tricks unless you are trying to prevent declarer from pitching. But that was not the case here. Although I understand why she ruffed, she should think twice about it. |
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This hand also illustrates a principle that all good declarers understand and that is that defenders often have difficulty knowing what you have. Sometimes they can be induced into making a mistake. I am not saying you should declare assuming they will make a mistake. But in this case I had to knock out the Ace of clubs anyway, so I played it deceptively. |
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


