UP|40|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The bidding and play were straight forward. What I would like to discuss is Sandy's opening lead, which was fine. Let me discuss honor leads against NT. Let's save the Ace for later. The lead of the King asks partner to signal positive attitude with the Ace or Jack or Queen. It is typically done from KQ10 or KQJ. But sometimes with AKxxx you might choose to lead the King, although I prefer low. |
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The lead of the King asks for an attitude signal. You signal high with an honor. The lead of the Queen is usually from QJ10 or QJ9 sometimes from AQJxx. Now the lead of the Jack depends on whether or not you play coded 10s and 9s. If you do not play coded 10s and 9s, you lead Jack from J109, J108, KJ10, or AJ10. So, playing standard leads, Dee in this hand would lead the Jack of clubs on opening lead-if she were to lead. |
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Many experts prefer coded 10s and 9s, which helps them figure out if partner has KJ10 or AJ10 or not. If you play coded 10s and 9s, then you have to lead J only from J109 or J108. Playing coded, the lead of the Jack denies anything higher. From AJ10 and KJ10, playing coded, you lead the 10. Some people say that shows "0 or two higher" but in fact it is a bit more complicated than that. It often shows KJ10 or AJ10. It also is done from 109xxx. |
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It either shows a broken sequence with the J10, or it shows nothing higher than the 10, partner can usually figure it out. The reason for playing coded 10s is that the J denies a higher honor, so it is easier for partner to figure out leader's exact holding playing coded 10s. Coded 9s are similar, they either show nothing higher than the 9, or a broken sequence with the 109, e.g. A109 or K109 or Q109. |
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, the lead of the Ace in NT is rare but it does have a special meaning. It is typically done from an almost solid suit, often AKJ. It asks partner to pitch an honor (K, Q, or J) most often the Q. You want partner to unblock. If partner has no honor then she gives count. To summarize, King asks for attitude, Ace asks for unblock or count and in real life you usually lead fourth best.|
PG| ***** 140 ***** |


